         <div type="translation">
 	<p n="1-8">Success! A cave and drinking cistern: the meritorious gift of the renunciant Sāpā — daughter of Dhammaṇṇaka of Dheṇukākaḍa who is dear to his family — pupil of the reverend elder Bodhika [and?] Poṇaka (Skt. Pūrṇaka?), together with her sister Ratiṇṇikā and together with the entire group of her relatives and connections. Established for the universal order of monks, for eight … individuals (?), on behalf of her mother and father, and for the purpose of the happiness and welfare of the whole world.</p>
    <p n="8-9">And an <foreign>akṣayanīvī</foreign> is given to the order of monks. And from this a cloth money of sixteen is to be given to the order of monks and a <foreign>paṭika</foreign> in the (hot) season.</p>
         </div>
          
          
          
          
         <div type="commentary">
           <p>B+B and G do not indicate the spacing between words. The upper left corner of the inscription is now peeled off, resulting in a loss of akṣaras in the first two lines. However, it was intact when West made his eye-copy and the reading is secure.</p> 
         </div>
          
          
          
          
